The White Pigeon Prairie Land Office in [[White Pigeon, Michigan]] is the oldest surviving land office in [[Michigan]] and was in business 1831–1834.<ref>{{usurped|1=[https://archive.today/20120904144145/http://www.michmarkers.com/startup.asp?startpage=L1205.htm Michigan Markers]}}</ref> It is designated as a [[Michigan State Historic Site]]. The United States land offices were the federal government agency that was primarily responsible for the sale and of public land to individual purchasers.  Michigan's first land office was established in [[Detroit, MI|Detroit]] in 1804.  The US Land office in White Pigeon was the third office to open in Michigan and was created on the Sauk Trail (today U.S. 12) as pioneers were moving west in search of viable land..,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/b/bhlead/umich-bhl-851856?view=text |title=Michigan State Land Office Board records: 1816-1924  |publisher=University of Michigan | website=Bentley Historical Library |access-date=21 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michigan.org/property/the-white-pigeon-land-office/ |title=The White Pigeon Land Office  |publisher=Pure Michigan |website=Michigan.org |access-date=21 September 2016}}</ref>
The U.S. started issuing land in Michigan after the [[1821 Treaty of Chicago]], in which the [[Potawatomi]] and other tribes turned over their land,  was signed in 1821. The White Pigeon land office operated for 4 years from 1831 to 1834.  During that time over a quarter million acres of land were sold from this office at a rate of $1.25 per acre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michmarkers.com/startup.asp?startpage=L1205.htm |title=Michigan Markers  |publisher=The Michigan Historical Marker Web Site|website=michmarkers.com |access-date=21 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230558/http://www.michmarkers.com/startup.asp?startpage=L1205.htm |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>  In 1834, the White Pigeon register Abraham S. Edwards and receiver, Thomas C. Sheldon moved to the newly created land office in Bronson-now Kalamazoo.
{{commons category|General Land Office (White Pigeon, Michigan)}}

