{{Ordination
He was [[Dean of Lichfield]] from July 1603 until he became [[Dean of Worcester]] on 20 December 1604. Montague was elected [[Bishop of Bath and Wells]] on 29 March 1608,<ref>{{CCEd |type=appointment |id=147638 |name=Montague, James |location=Bath and Wells |accessed=29 March 2015 }}</ref> his [[confirmation of bishops|election was confirmed]] on 15 April<ref>{{CCEd |type=appointment |id=234218 |name=Montague, James |location=Bath and Wells |accessed=29 March 2015 }}</ref> and he was enthroned and installed at [[Wells Cathedral]] on 14 May 1608;<ref>{{CCEd |type=appointment |id=147641 |name=Montague, James |location=Bath and Wells |accessed=29 March 2015 }}</ref> he was translated to become [[Bishop of Winchester]] on 3 July 1616.<ref>''Concise Dictionary of National Biography''</ref> As Bishop of Bath and Wells, Montague spent considerable sums in restoring both the Bishop's Palace at Wells and Bath Abbey; this last, roofless since the Reformation, was re-roofed out of his own pocket. He actively supported the Baths themselves, aware that the ‘towne liveth wholly by them’. In 1613, perhaps at his behest, the Queen, Anne of Denmark, visited the town to take the waters: the Queen's Bath was named after her. The cue for the visit may have been the completion of the restoration work to Bath Abbey, the last instalment of which had been paid for two years previously. In the same year (probably) and at Wells (probably), Montague staged a "Panegiricall entertainement" for the queen, whose cast included the character of [[Joseph of Arimathea]], who presented a bough from the [[Holy Thorn of Glastonbury]] to the queen, the first explicit link between Joseph and the Thorn.<ref>Stout, Adam (2020) ''Glastonbury Holy Thorn: Story of a Legend'' Green & Pleasant Publishing, pp.28-30  {{ISBN| 978-1-9162686-1-6}}</ref> At Bath and Wells, he contributed to the legend of the [[Holy Thorn of Glastonbury]], in an entertainment for [[Anne of Denmark]], when the character of [[Joseph of Arimathea]] presented boughs to the Queen.<ref name="isleofavalon">{{cite web|url=https://www.isleofavalon.co.uk/history/thornwaters.html|title=Isle of Avalon &#124; the History of Glastonbury|publisher=isleofavalon.co.uk|access-date=2014-04-12}}</ref> He is commemorated by an alabaster monument in [[Bath Abbey]].<ref name="historicbritain">{{cite web|url=http://www.historicbritain.com/vendor.aspx?v=bathabbey&extradetails=true&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Bath Abbey: Places to visit in Bath|publisher=historicbritain.com|access-date=2014-04-12}}</ref>

